            "title": "Japan carefully considering implications of consumption tax suspension, finance minister says",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>TOKYO, Jan 30 (Reuters) - Japanese Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi is carefully considering the implications for fiscal sustainability of a consumption tax suspension and is consulting with the Finance Ministry, Finance Minister Satsuki Katayama said on Friday.</p><p>\n              Takaichi has proposed halting the 8% consumption tax on food and drinks for a period of two years, which precipitated a jump in government bond yields and a decline in the yen on market fears it could require funding through more debt issuance.</p><!-- Article --><p>\n              Speaking at a campaign event in support of a lower house election candidate in Tokyo, Katayama said that she had explained the justification for the tax cut at the World Economic Forum's annual gathering in Davos earlier this month and that current market conditions had stabilised.</p><p></p><p> (Reporting by Tamiyuki Kihara; Writing by Anton Bridge; Editing by Jamie Freed)</p></div>",
